mapproperties.key: This diagram is used to link human profiles to a human. Every profile has a reference to a diagram that defines it. Each profile stores a subset of information of a human. Currently, three profiles has been defined:

The activity diagram is used to specify a set of activities linked directly (if they are performed sequentially) or through flow controls that allows a designer to define alternative paths of activities depending on the flow control objects.

Entities used to specify a set of sequential time intervals. Every TimeInterval object should have a reference to a activity diagram (ActivityDiagram) in order to define a set of activities for the given time interval. A time interval may have a reference to a start time of the interval. If a TimeInterval has a time assigned, then the activities will not begin until the clock reach to this time. Otherwise, the activities of the TimeInterval will start just after the activities of the previous interval are finished.

Parkinson's Disease (PD) diagram that includes the main elements of the disease. The first concept of the disease is the stage (PDDiseaseStage). There are 5 stages that are usually called E1, E2, E3, E4 and E5. This stage is set in the NamePDStageField. A PD stage has reference to a diagram that specifies when the intakes of medicines take place. Finally, a PD stage has a set of symptoms that are linked using Symptoms relationship.

A symptom (PDSymptom object) has a name or type (PDSymptomTypeField) and a reference to its evolution (SymptomEvoField). A symptom has four levels and can change along time (NONE, LOW, MEDIUM AND HIGH). Besides every symptom involve a set of limitations that are modeled using a TaskFilter diagram.There are three types of references to task filters (LOWTaskFilterR, MEDIUMTaskFilterR and HIGHTaskFilterR). Each one is applied depending on the state of the symptom. For example, if a tremor symptom is in a low state, then the filter applied will be those whose type is LOWTaskFilterR.
SequentialTaskDiagram can be used to define a sequence of tasks that should be performed one after another.
RandomTaskDiagram is used to define a set of tasks that have to be performed but it is not important the order.
This diagram is used to know information about the medication intakes of a patient: when a patient has to take the medication, the amount of the doses and what medicines.

Elements of the SymptomEvolutionDiagram. It is basically a metamodel of a state machine. There are four states, one for each intensity level of the symptom (NONE, LOW, MEDIUM and HIGH). Transitions between states are modeled by SymptomTransition relationship. The sources of the relationship should be one symptom state at least, and besides, it could has one or more PreCondition objects (Condition or BEvent).
The diagram is pretty similar to the Parkinson's Disease diagram but it has some fields more opened.It is used to model any disease: the stage, the medication, symptoms and limitations.

The activity diagram is used to specify a set of activities linked directly (if they are performed sequentially) or through flow controls that allows a designer to define alternative paths of activities depending on the flow control objects.

An activity (BActivity) has reference to a diagram of tasks (SeqTaskDiagramField). An activity can be linked with other activity using NextActivity relationships. If two tasks are joined by this relationship means that both activities are performed one after another.

A flow control has a Condition object that is evaluated. Depending on the evaluation is successful or not the next activity or flow controller will be different. If the condition is successful, the next element will be given by TrueFlow relationship. Otherwise, the next one will be pointed by FalseFlow relationship.
Concrete diagram, it just sets the representation of the elements of the ActivityDiagram.

Social profile includes social information of the human. It models personal information such as age, sex, house where live in, social class, studies level and profession (with an active field to indicate if the human is still working). Besides, a SocialNetwork object includes all the relationships of a human with others humans (such as wife of, husband of, caregiver of, etcetera). All these information is accesible from PersonalInfo object.
This diagram just includes the available social relationships of a human.
Concrete diagram, it just sets the representation of the SocialSpecDiagram.

Concrete diagram, it just sets the representation of the elements in cTimeMM.

A filter diagram is used to change the behaviour of the human at task level. It can be used to model human limitations (e.g. he/she can't pick up an object whose weight is greater than x) or to model human preferences (e.g. what is his/her favourite chair where he/she like to sit down?).

Every filter can have a condition element that sets if the filter is applied or not. If the element condition is missing, the filter is always applied. Two filters can be connected be two relations: NextFilter and FAlternative. If a filter is applied the next filter to be considered is given by the NextFilter relationship. Otherwise, the next filter is given by FAlternative relationship.

Four types of filters has been identified:

  1. FTaskSelectorFilter is commonly used as the first filter in order to select the tasks that will be processed in a next filter.
  2. FReplaceTaskFilter changes a task for other. For example, ask for something instead of doing oneself.
  3. FUnableFilter can be seen as a FReplaceTaskFilter but the replaced task is the empty set. NextFilter relationship has no sense in this filter.
  4. FModifyFilter has in turn four subtypes that each one changes one of the four fields of a task: FDelayFilter (duration), FModifyPlaceFilter (location), FChangeToolFilter (tool) and FChangeTargetObjFilter (target object).
Concrete diagram, it just sets the representation of the FilterDiagram.
